& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Mucosal melanomas (MMs) are rare and aggressive tumors that arise from melanocytes in the mucosal tissues that line the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and urogenital tracts. Most MMs occur during the 6th and 7th decades of life. MMs may be asymptomatic but may also cause bleeding, pain, and itching, depending on the site of origin. Because of their asymptomatic or oligosymptomatic nature and the difficulty of visualizing them in some cases, they are often advanced tumors at patient presentation. MM staging varies depending on the site of the primary tumor. A simplified staging system allows classification of clinically localized disease as stage I, regional nodal involvement as stage II, and distant metastasis as stage III. MM differs genetically from its cutaneous counterparts. Common drivers in cutaneous melanoma such as B-raf proto-oncogene serine/threonine kinase (<i>BRAF</i>) have a lower mutation rate in MM, whereas mutations of other genes including the KIT proto-oncogene, receptor tyrosine kinase (<i>KIT</i>) and splicing factor 3b subunit 1 gene (<i>SF3B1</i>) are more common in MM. Complete resection is the best curative option. However, surgical intervention with wide local excision and negative margins may be difficult to attain because of the local anatomy and the extent of disease. In addition, despite aggressive surgical resection, most patients develop local recurrence and metastatic disease. Recent advances in the treatment of melanoma include immunotherapy and targeted therapy. Unfortunately, MMs have a relatively poor prognosis, with an overall 5-year survival rate of 25%.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div><div role="paragraph"><i>An earlier incorrect version of this article appeared online and in print. This article was corrected on January 25, 2022.</i></div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210063">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210063">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="(A) Photomicrograph shows vulvar MM, with squamous mucosa and atypical melanocytes in a lentiginous pattern of growth and atypical cells in the lamina propria, indicating invasion. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×200.) (B) Photomicrograph shows the invasive component of the vulvar MM with diffuse expression of MLANA. (Immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×100.) (C) Photomicrograph of a double immunohistochemical study shows melanoma cells that are positive for MITF (brown) and endothelial cells positive for podoplanin (D2–40) (red). (Immunohistochemical stain for MITF [nuclear, brown]) and D2–40 [cytoplasmic, red]; original magnification, ×100.) (D) Photomicrograph shows an in situ sinonasal MM of the respiratory epithelium. Melanoma in situ may be difficult to identify at routine histologic examination. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.) (E) Photomicrograph shows in situ (arrow) and invasive melanoma cells that are positive for S100. (Immunohistochemical S100 stain; original magnification, ×40.) (F) Photomicrograph shows melanoma cells involving both the respiratory epithelium (arrow) and the lamina propria of the sinonasal tract stained with the nuclear marker SOX10. (Immunohistochemical SOX10 stain, original magnification, ×40.) (G) Photomicrograph shows MM with polypoid architecture in the squamous mucosa of the esophagus and glandular epithelium comprising the cardias and esophageal glands (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.) (H) Photomicrograph shows esophageal in situ MM involving squamous epithelium, overlying a large invasive component. (H-E stain, original magnification, ×200.) (I) Photomicrograph shows an MM with diffuse expression of KIT. (Immunohistochemical stain; original magnification ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig1.jpeg" height="2698" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. <b>(A)</b> Photomicrograph shows vulvar MM, with squamous mucosa and atypical melanocytes in a lentiginous pattern of growth and atypical cells in the lamina propria, indicating invasion. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×200.) <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph shows the invasive component of the vulvar MM with diffuse expression of <i>MLANA.</i> (Immunohistochemical stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph of a double immunohistochemical study shows melanoma cells that are positive for <i>MITF</i> (brown) and endothelial cells positive for podoplanin (D2–40) (red). (Immunohistochemical stain for <i>MITF</i> [nuclear, brown]) and D2–40 [cytoplasmic, red]; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph shows an in situ sinonasal MM of the respiratory epithelium. Melanoma in situ may be difficult to identify at routine histologic examination. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×200.) <b>(E)</b> Photomicrograph shows in situ (arrow) and invasive melanoma cells that are positive for S100. (Immunohistochemical S100 stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(F)</b> Photomicrograph shows melanoma cells involving both the respiratory epithelium (arrow) and the lamina propria of the sinonasal tract stained with the nuclear marker <i>SOX10</i>. (Immunohistochemical <i>SOX10</i> stain, original magnification, ×40.) <b>(G)</b> Photomicrograph shows MM with polypoid architecture in the squamous mucosa of the esophagus and glandular epithelium comprising the cardias and esophageal glands (arrows). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×20.) <b>(H)</b> Photomicrograph shows esophageal in situ MM involving squamous epithelium, overlying a large invasive component. (H-E stain, original magnification, ×200.) <b>(I)</b> Photomicrograph shows an MM with diffuse expression of <i>KIT.</i> (Immunohistochemical stain; original magnification ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows that mutations in KIT lead to aberrant downstream signaling through the PI3K (alias of PIK3CA) and NRAS pathways to stimulate cellular division. BAD = BCL2-associated agonist of cell death, caspaces = apoptosis-related cysteine peptidase, cyclyn D1 (CCND1), FOXO = forkhead box (alias of FOXO1), GSK3 = glycogen synthase kinase 3 (alias of GSK3A), IKK = inhibitor of nuclear factor kappa kinase, MEK = mitogen-activated protein kinase (alias of MAP2K1), mTOR = mechanistic target of rapamycin kinase, PI3 = peptidase inhibitor 3, PRAS40 = proline-rich AKT substrate (alias of AKT1S1)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig2.jpeg" height="2631" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustration shows that mutations in <i>KIT</i> lead to aberrant downstream signaling through the <i>PI3K</i> (alias of <i>PIK3CA)</i> and <i>NRAS</i> pathways to stimulate cellular division. <i>BAD</i> = <i>BCL2</i>-associated agonist of cell death, <i>caspaces</i> = apoptosis-related cysteine peptidase, cyclyn D1 (<i>CCND1</i>), <i>FOXO</i> = forkhead box (alias of <i>FOXO1</i>), <i>GSK3</i> = glycogen synthase kinase 3 (alias of <i>GSK3A</i>), <i>IKK</i> = inhibitor of nuclear factor kappa kinase, <i>MEK</i> = mitogen-activated protein kinase (alias of <i>MAP2K1), mTOR</i> = mechanistic target of rapamycin kinase, <i>PI3</i> = peptidase inhibitor 3, <i>PRAS40</i> = proline-rich AKT substrate (alias of <i>AKT1S1</i>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Primary MM in an 80-year-old man with left nasal congestion. (A) Axial noncontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a lesion in the left nasal cavity (arrows). * = left sphenoid sinus. (B) Axial T2-weighted image shows low signal intensity (arrows) and obstruction in the left sphenoid sinus (*). (C) Axial CT image shows no bone destruction. (D) Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake in the left nasal cavity mass (arrows), with an SUV of 10. Examination revealed a black-pigmented mass in the left nasal cavity. Biopsy was performed and led to the diagnosis of primary MM. The patient was treated with endoscopic endonasal resection of the tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig3.jpeg" height="2703" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Primary MM in an 80-year-old man with left nasal congestion. <b>(A)</b> Axial noncontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a lesion in the left nasal cavity (arrows). * = left sphenoid sinus. <b>(B)</b> Axial T2-weighted image shows low signal intensity (arrows) and obstruction in the left sphenoid sinus (*). <b>(C)</b> Axial CT image shows no bone destruction. <b>(D)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake in the left nasal cavity mass (arrows), with an SUV of 10. Examination revealed a black-pigmented mass in the left nasal cavity. Biopsy was performed and led to the diagnosis of primary MM. The patient was treated with endoscopic endonasal resection of the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Esophageal MM in a 72-year-old woman with dysphagia. (A) Barium esophagogram shows a polypoid mass in the lower esophagus (arrow), causing partial obstruction to the passage of oral contrast material into the stomach. (B) Axial fused PET/CT image shows FDG uptake in the polypoid esophageal mass (arrow), with an SUV of 5.6 and no evidence of distant metastases. Biopsy results showed a primary esophageal MM. (C) Axial intravenous contrast–enhanced CT image from a surveillance examination 15 months after esophagectomy with gastric pull-up (*) shows a new posterior mediastinal metastatic lymph node (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig4.jpeg" height="1336" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Esophageal MM in a 72-year-old woman with dysphagia. <b>(A)</b> Barium esophagogram shows a polypoid mass in the lower esophagus (arrow), causing partial obstruction to the passage of oral contrast material into the stomach. <b>(B)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows FDG uptake in the polypoid esophageal mass (arrow), with an SUV of 5.6 and no evidence of distant metastases. Biopsy results showed a primary esophageal MM. <b>(C)</b> Axial intravenous contrast–enhanced CT image from a surveillance examination 15 months after esophagectomy with gastric pull-up (*) shows a new posterior mediastinal metastatic lymph node (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven anorectal MM and bleeding in a 48-year-old woman who underwent multiple prior refractory therapies.(A, B) Follow-up axial (A) and sagittal (B) T2-weighted MR images show a large lobulated tumor (white arrows) occupying the entire pelvic cavity and extending to the anal canal. The vagina (black arrow in B) is compressed, displaced anteriorly, and filled with a small amount of fluid and air. A Foley catheter is present in the collapsed and anteriorly displaced bladder (*) and urethra, without tumor invasion. (C, D) Diffusion-weighted MR image (C) and ADC map (D) show restricted diffusion (b = 800 sec/mm2) in the tumor (arrows). The patient previously underwent hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig5.jpeg" height="2651" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Biopsy-proven anorectal MM and bleeding in a 48-year-old woman who underwent multiple prior refractory therapies.<b>(A, B)</b> Follow-up axial <b>(A)</b> and sagittal <b>(B)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a large lobulated tumor (white arrows) occupying the entire pelvic cavity and extending to the anal canal. The vagina (black arrow in <b>B</b>) is compressed, displaced anteriorly, and filled with a small amount of fluid and air. A Foley catheter is present in the collapsed and anteriorly displaced bladder (*) and urethra, without tumor invasion. <b>(C, D)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR image <b>(C)</b> and ADC map <b>(D)</b> show restricted diffusion (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) in the tumor (arrows). The patient previously underwent hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Anorectal MM in a 77-year-old woman with rectal bleeding (A) Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows an anal mass (arrows). (B, C) Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (B) and ADC map (C) show restricted diffusion (arrows) (b = 1500 sec/mm2). (D) Axial fused PET/CT image shows an anal mass (arrows) with intense FDG uptake and an SUV of 8.7, with no distant metastases. Biopsy results revealed primary anorectal MM. The patient was treated with transanal surgical resection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig6.jpeg" height="2612" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Anorectal MM in a 77-year-old woman with rectal bleeding <b>(A)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows an anal mass (arrows). <b>(B, C)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image <b>(B)</b> and ADC map <b>(C)</b> show restricted diffusion (arrows) (<i>b</i> = 1500 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>). <b>(D)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows an anal mass (arrows) with intense FDG uptake and an SUV of 8.7, with no distant metastases. Biopsy results revealed primary anorectal MM. The patient was treated with transanal surgical resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Anorectal MM in a 69-year-old man with worsening constipation and rectal bleeding. (A, B) Axial (A) and coronal (B) T2-weighted MR images show a lobulated heterogeneous mass in the distal rectum and rectoanal junction, with extension into the perirectal fat (white arrows), abutment of the left levator ani muscle (yellow arrow in A), and an irregular metastatic lymph node along the mesorectal fascia (black arrow in B), abutting the right levator ani muscle (yellow arrow in B). (C) Axial T2-weighted MR image shows an anterior perirectal metastatic lymph node at the 10-o'clock position, abutting the mesorectal fascia (yellow arrow), and a perirectal lymph node at the 4-o'clock position (black arrow). Biopsy results revealed primary anorectal MM. The patient was treated with systemic therapy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig7.jpeg" height="1222" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Anorectal MM in a 69-year-old man with worsening constipation and rectal bleeding. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and coronal <b>(B)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a lobulated heterogeneous mass in the distal rectum and rectoanal junction, with extension into the perirectal fat (white arrows), abutment of the left levator ani muscle (yellow arrow in <b>A</b>), and an irregular metastatic lymph node along the mesorectal fascia (black arrow in <b>B</b>), abutting the right levator ani muscle (yellow arrow in <b>B</b>). <b>(C)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows an anterior perirectal metastatic lymph node at the 10-o'clock position, abutting the mesorectal fascia (yellow arrow), and a perirectal lymph node at the 4-o'clock position (black arrow). Biopsy results revealed primary anorectal MM. The patient was treated with systemic therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Vulvar MM in a 63-year-old woman with a history of bright red blood when wiping after urination. (A, B) Axial T2-weighted (A) and T1-weighted contrast-enhanced fat-saturated (B) MR images show a lesion measuring 1.8 × 0.7 cm in the right vulva (white arrow). A metastatic right superficial inguinal lymph node can be seen (black arrow). (C) Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake (arrow) with an SUV of 16 and a metastatic right external iliac lymph node (not shown). Biopsy of the vulvar lesion revealed primary MM. The patient was treated with four cycles of neoadjuvant ipilimumab and nivolumab followed by right partial vulvectomy with bilateral pelvic-inguinal lymphadenectomy followed by adjuvant radiation and adjuvant nivolumab therapy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig8.jpeg" height="1247" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Vulvar MM in a 63-year-old woman with a history of bright red blood when wiping after urination. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(A)</b> and T1-weighted contrast-enhanced fat-saturated <b>(B)</b> MR images show a lesion measuring 1.8 × 0.7 cm in the right vulva (white arrow). A metastatic right superficial inguinal lymph node can be seen (black arrow). <b>(C)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake (arrow) with an SUV of 16 and a metastatic right external iliac lymph node (not shown). Biopsy of the vulvar lesion revealed primary MM. The patient was treated with four cycles of neoadjuvant ipilimumab and nivolumab followed by right partial vulvectomy with bilateral pelvic-inguinal lymphadenectomy followed by adjuvant radiation and adjuvant nivolumab therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Vaginal MM in a 78-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. (A, B) Sagittal (A) and axial (B) T2-weighted MR images with vaginal gel (*) show a hypointense lobulated elongated mass in the lower anterior wall of the vagina (arrows), reaching to the vaginal introitus. It appears to be confined to the vaginal wall, without evidence of extravaginal extension. No tumor is seen in the anal hiatus. (C) Intravenous contrast–enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows intense enhancement of the vaginal mass (arrows). Biopsy results showed a primary vaginal MM."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig9.jpeg" height="1248" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Vaginal MM in a 78-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. <b>(A, B)</b> Sagittal <b>(A)</b> and axial <b>(B)</b> T2-weighted MR images with vaginal gel (*) show a hypointense lobulated elongated mass in the lower anterior wall of the vagina (arrows), reaching to the vaginal introitus. It appears to be confined to the vaginal wall, without evidence of extravaginal extension. No tumor is seen in the anal hiatus. <b>(C)</b> Intravenous contrast–enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows intense enhancement of the vaginal mass (arrows). Biopsy results showed a primary vaginal MM.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Vaginal MM in a 66-year-old woman with postcoital bleeding. (A) Sagittal T2-weighted MR image with vaginal gel (*) shows an anterior vaginal mass (arrows). Biopsy results showed a primary vaginal MM. The patient was treated with cisplatin, vinblastine, dacarbazine, and pembrolizumab. (B) Posttreatment follow-up sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a significant interval decrease in the size of the mass (arrows). The patient underwent total hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy and partial vaginectomy. (C) Surveillance sagittal T2-weighted MR image acquired 8 months after surgery shows recurrent tumor in the vagina (arrows). * = bladder."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig10.jpeg" height="1239" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Vaginal MM in a 66-year-old woman with postcoital bleeding. <b>(A)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image with vaginal gel (*) shows an anterior vaginal mass (arrows). Biopsy results showed a primary vaginal MM. The patient was treated with cisplatin, vinblastine, dacarbazine, and pembrolizumab. <b>(B)</b> Posttreatment follow-up sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a significant interval decrease in the size of the mass (arrows). The patient underwent total hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy and partial vaginectomy. <b>(C)</b> Surveillance sagittal T2-weighted MR image acquired 8 months after surgery shows recurrent tumor in the vagina (arrows). * = bladder.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Cervical MM in a 62-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. (A–C) Sagittal T2-weighted (A) and axial diffusion-weighted (B) MR images and ADC map (C) show a large lobulated mass in the uterine cervix (arrows), extending into the lower uterine segment, with restricted diffusion characterized by signal hyperintensity and a low ADC. * in A = bladder. (D) Axial fused PET/CT image shows a hypermetabolic cervical mass (arrow) with an SUV of 22 and no evidence of distant metastasis. Biopsy results showed primary cervical MM. The patient was treated with total hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig11.jpeg" height="2694" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Cervical MM in a 62-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. <b>(A–C)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted <b>(A)</b> and axial diffusion-weighted <b>(B)</b> MR images and ADC map <b>(C)</b> show a large lobulated mass in the uterine cervix (arrows), extending into the lower uterine segment, with restricted diffusion characterized by signal hyperintensity and a low ADC. * in <b>A</b> = bladder. <b>(D)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows a hypermetabolic cervical mass (arrow) with an SUV of 22 and no evidence of distant metastasis. Biopsy results showed primary cervical MM. The patient was treated with total hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Cervical MM in a 36-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. (A, B) Sagittal T2-weighted (A) and T1-weighted contrast-enhanced (B) MR images show a large lobulated mass in the cervix (arrows), extending inferiorly and distending the vagina with heterogeneous enhancement and areas of necrosis (arrows). Biopsy results revealed primary cervical MM. (C) Coronal staging maximum intensity projection PET/CT image shows the large pelvic mass and extensive metastatic disease (arrows), involving the lungs, liver, retroperitoneal lymph nodes, and subcutaneous tissues."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig12.jpeg" height="2203" width="3791" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Cervical MM in a 36-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. <b>(A, B)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted <b>(A)</b> and T1-weighted contrast-enhanced <b>(B)</b> MR images show a large lobulated mass in the cervix (arrows), extending inferiorly and distending the vagina with heterogeneous enhancement and areas of necrosis (arrows). Biopsy results revealed primary cervical MM. <b>(C)</b> Coronal staging maximum intensity projection PET/CT image shows the large pelvic mass and extensive metastatic disease (arrows), involving the lungs, liver, retroperitoneal lymph nodes, and subcutaneous tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Cervical MM in a 52-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. (A) Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a mass (arrow) originating from the anterior cervix extending into the vaginal canal. Biopsy showed primary cervical MM, and intracavitary brachytherapy was performed, followed by total hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy. (B) Sagittal MR image acquired 9 months after treatment shows a new large recurrent mass in the pelvis (arrows) and lobulated metastatic adenopathy at the level of the bifurcation, encasing the left external and internal iliac vessels (arrowheads), and a small amount of fluid in the pelvis (*). (C) Coronal maximum intensity projection PET/CT image shows extensive metastatic disease (arrows) with bone lesions of the eighth rib on the right side and the T11 and L1 vertebrae, multiple hepatic metastases, retroperitoneal and pelvic metastatic adenopathy, and a large pelvic recurrent mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig13.jpeg" height="2200" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Cervical MM in a 52-year-old woman with vaginal bleeding. <b>(A)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a mass (arrow) originating from the anterior cervix extending into the vaginal canal. Biopsy showed primary cervical MM, and intracavitary brachytherapy was performed, followed by total hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy. <b>(B)</b> Sagittal MR image acquired 9 months after treatment shows a new large recurrent mass in the pelvis (arrows) and lobulated metastatic adenopathy at the level of the bifurcation, encasing the left external and internal iliac vessels (arrowheads), and a small amount of fluid in the pelvis (*). <b>(C)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection PET/CT image shows extensive metastatic disease (arrows) with bone lesions of the eighth rib on the right side and the T11 and L1 vertebrae, multiple hepatic metastases, retroperitoneal and pelvic metastatic adenopathy, and a large pelvic recurrent mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Urethral MM in a 75-year-old woman with a history of urinary incontinence. (A, B) Axial (A) and sagittal (B) T2-weighted MR images show a mass in the urethra (arrows) measuring 1.5 cm. The urinary bladder (* in B) is also seen. (C) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mass in the urethra (arrows) that is poorly delineated. (D) Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake (arrows), with an SUV of 12. Cystourethroscopy and biopsy results revealed a primary urethral MM."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig14.jpeg" height="3444" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Urethral MM in a 75-year-old woman with a history of urinary incontinence. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and sagittal <b>(B)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a mass in the urethra (arrows) measuring 1.5 cm. The urinary bladder (* in <b>B</b>) is also seen. <b>(C)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mass in the urethra (arrows) that is poorly delineated. <b>(D)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows intense FDG uptake (arrows), with an SUV of 12. Cystourethroscopy and biopsy results revealed a primary urethral MM.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Urethral MM in a 73-year-old man who presented with intermittent hematuria and difficulty urinating. Axial (A, B) and sagittal (C) T2-weighted MR images show a mass measuring 2.8 × 2.4 cm (white arrows) arising from the penile urethra, immediately distal to the glans penis, extending into the corpora spongiosa and corpora cavernosa (*). Note the Foley catheter (yellow arrow). Cystourethroscopy and biopsy of the mass revealed primary urethral MM. The patient was treated with radical penectomy, perineal urethrostomy, and inguinal lymph node dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig15.jpeg" height="1246" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Urethral MM in a 73-year-old man who presented with intermittent hematuria and difficulty urinating. Axial <b>(A, B)</b> and sagittal <b>(C)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a mass measuring 2.8 × 2.4 cm (white arrows) arising from the penile urethra, immediately distal to the glans penis, extending into the corpora spongiosa and corpora cavernosa (*). Note the Foley catheter (yellow arrow). Cystourethroscopy and biopsy of the mass revealed primary urethral MM. The patient was treated with radical penectomy, perineal urethrostomy, and inguinal lymph node dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Bladder MM in a 32-year-old man with hematuria. (A, B) Axial (A) and coronal reconstructed (B) CT images show a small nodular area of wall thickening (arrow) in the right lateral bladder wall. Cystoscopic transurethral biopsy results revealed primary bladder MM involving the lamina propria. Physical examination and whole-body imaging (not shown) excluded the possibility of a primary melanoma from another site. The patient was treated with neoadjuvant ipilimumab plus nivolumab and transurethral surgical resection. (C) Surveillance axial chest CT image acquired 5 months later shows a single metastasis in the right lung (arrows) that was also treated with surgical resection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210063/asset/images/large/rg.2021210063.fig16.jpeg" height="1248" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Bladder MM in a 32-year-old man with hematuria. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and coronal reconstructed <b>(B)</b> CT images show a small nodular area of wall thickening (arrow) in the right lateral bladder wall. Cystoscopic transurethral biopsy results revealed primary bladder MM involving the lamina propria. Physical examination and whole-body imaging (not shown) excluded the possibility of a primary melanoma from another site. The patient was treated with neoadjuvant ipilimumab plus nivolumab and transurethral surgical resection. <b>(C)</b> Surveillance axial chest CT image acquired 5 months later shows a single metastasis in the right lung (arrows) that was also treated with surgical resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210063&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">McLaughlin CC, Wu XC, Jemal A, Martin HJ, Roche LM, Chen VW. Incidence of noncutaneous melanomas in the U.S. <em>Cancer</em> 2005;103(5):1000–1007.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/cncr.20866">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15651058/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Incidence+of+noncu